7.4 Copying, killing, yanking a rectangular region
==================================================

A rectangle can be copied or killed, then yanked somewhere else.

   Select a region, press ‚Äė<insert>‚Äô, then:
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äėc‚Äô to copy
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äėk‚Äô to kill
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äėy‚Äô to yank (aka paste)

   This is similar to the ‚ÄėEmacs‚Äô standard rectangle handling:
   ‚ÄĘ ‚ÄėC-x r r‚Äô copy rectangle to register
   ‚ÄĘ ‚ÄėC-x r k‚Äô kill rectangle
   ‚ÄĘ ‚ÄėC-x r y‚Äô yank killed rectangle

   The first difference is that ‚ÄėUniline‚Äô rectangles, when killed and
yanked, do not move surrounding characters.

   The second difference is that the white characters of the yanked
rectangle are considered transparent.  As a result, only non-blank parts
of the yanked rectangle are over-printed.

   ‚ÄėUniline‚Äô and ‚ÄėEmacs‚Äô standard rectangle share the same storage for
copied and killed rectangles, namely the ‚Äėkilled-rectangle‚Äô Lisp
variable.  So, a rectangle can be killed one way, and yanked another
way.


