       ...a.hole/////           ...a.hole/////


   A hollow shape is a contiguous region of identical characters (not
necessarily blank), surrounded by a boundary of different characters.
The end of the buffer in any direction is also considered a boundary.

   Put the cursor anywhere in the hole.  Then type:

   ‚Äė<insert> i‚Äô

   Answer by giving a character to fill the hole.

   If instead of a character, ‚ÄėSPC‚Äô or ‚ÄėDEL‚Äô is typed, then a shade of
grey character is picked.  ‚ÄėSPC‚Äô selects a darker grey than the one the
point is on, while ‚ÄėDEL‚Äô selects a lighter.  There are 5 shades of grey
in the UNICODE standard: ‚Äė" ‚ĖĎ‚Ėí‚Ėď‚Ėą"‚Äô.  Those grey characters are well
supported by the suggested fonts.

   ‚ÄėC-y‚Äô is also an option.  The first character in the top of the kill
ring will be chosen as the filling character.  (The kill ring is filled
by functions like ‚ÄėC-k‚Äô or ‚ÄėM-w‚Äô, unrelated to ‚ÄėUniline‚Äô).

   Typing ‚Äė<return>‚Äô or ‚ÄėC-g‚Äô aborts the filling operation.

   A rectangular shape may also be filled.
   ‚ÄĘ Mark a region
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äė<insert> i‚Äô
   ‚ÄĘ answer which character should be used to fill.

   There is no limit on the area to fill.  Therefore, the filling
operation may flood the entire buffer (but no more).


