   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äė(set-frame-font "Agave" )‚Äô
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äė(set-frame-font "JuliaMono" )‚Äô
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äė(set-frame-font "FreeMono" )‚Äô
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äė(set-frame-font "Iosevka Comfy Fixed" )‚Äô
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äė(set-frame-font "Iosevka Comfy Wide Fixed")‚Äô
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äė(set-frame-font "Aporetic Sans Mono" )‚Äô
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äė(set-frame-font "Aporetic Serif Mono" )‚Äô
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äė(set-frame-font "Source Code Pro" )‚Äô

   Those fonts are known to support the required UNICODE characters, AND
display them as mono-space.  There are fonts advertised as mono-space
which give arbitrary widths to non-ASCII characters.  That is bad for
the kind of drawings done by ‚ÄėUniline‚Äô.

   You may want to try any of the suggested fonts.  Just hit the
corresponding entry in the ‚ÄėUniline‚Äô menu, or type ‚Äė<insert> f‚Äô.  You
may also execute the above Lisp commands like that:

   ‚ÄėM-: (set-frame-font "DejaVu Sans Mono")‚Äô

   This setting is for the current session only.  If you want to make it
permanent, you may use the ‚ÄėEmacs‚Äô customization:

   ‚Äė<insert> f *‚Äô

   or

   ‚ÄėM-x customize-face default‚Äô

   Beware that ‚ÄėEmacs‚Äô tries to compensate for missing UNICODE support
by the current font.  ‚ÄėEmacs‚Äô substitutes one font for another,
character per character.  The user may not notice until the drawings
done under ‚ÄėEmacs‚Äô are displayed on another text editor or on the Web.
Of course, using the suggested fonts and the UNICODEs drawn by ‚ÄėUniline‚Äô
keeps you away from those glitches.

   To know which font ‚ÄėEmacs‚Äô has chosen for a given character, type:

   ‚ÄėC-u C-x =‚Äô

   Note that none of those commands downloads a font from the Web.  The
font should already be available.


