11.3 One-liner menus
====================

The multi-lines menus in Hydra and Transient are quite useful for casual
users.  For seasoned users, those huge textual menus may distract them
from their workflow.

   It is now possible to switch to less distracting textual menus.  They
are displayed in the echo-area on a single line.

   To do so, type:
   ‚ÄĘ ‚ÄėC-t‚Äô within a sub-mode (glyph insertion mode, rectangle handling,
     etc.)
   ‚ÄĘ ‚ÄėC-h TAB‚Äô at the top-level.

   This will flip between the two sizes of textual menus.  It also
affects the welcome message, the one displayed when entering the
‚ÄėUniline‚Äô minor mode.

   The current size is controlled by the ‚Äėuniline-hint-style‚Äô variable:
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äėt‚Äô for full fledged messages over several lines
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äė1‚Äô for one-liner messages
   ‚ÄĘ ‚Äė0‚Äô for no message at all

   The variable is "buffer-local", which means that it can take distinct
values on distinct buffers.

   Its default value can be customized and saved for future sessions:

   ‚ÄėM-x customize-variable uniline-hint-style‚Äô

   After customization it can be changed later, on a buffer per buffer
basis, with the ‚ÄėC-t‚Äô or ‚ÄėC-h TAB‚Äô keys.

   Transient natively offers a similar setting: ‚Äėtransient-show-popup‚Äô.
(There is no such variable in Hydra).  It can be customized with ‚Äėt‚Äô,
‚Äėnil‚Äô, ‚Äė0‚Äô (zero), or a number.  This is similar but not exactly the
same as the Hydra behavior and the ‚Äėuniline-hint-style‚Äô.  the Transient
setting stays in effect until the ‚ÄėC-t‚Äô or ‚ÄėC-h TAB‚Äô keys are not used,
.  As soon as one of those keys is invoked, ‚Äėtransient-show-popup‚Äô is
toggled (which does not happens in Transient alone).  The change is kept
in effect throughout the ‚ÄėUniline‚Äô session, but no longer.


