14.3 Example: Lisp function to draw a plus sign
===============================================

For instance, if we want to create a function to draw a "plus" sign, we
can code it as follows:

     (defun uniline-draw-plus ()
       (interactive)
       (uniline-write-ri‚Üí 1)
       (uniline-write-dw‚Üď 1)
       (uniline-write-ri‚Üí 1)
       (uniline-write-dw‚Üď 1)
       (uniline-write-lf‚Üź 1)
       (uniline-write-dw‚Üď 1)
       (uniline-write-lf‚Üź 1)
       (uniline-write-up‚ÜĎ 1)
       (uniline-write-lf‚Üź 1)
       (uniline-write-up‚ÜĎ 1)
       (uniline-write-ri‚Üí 1)
       (uniline-write-up‚ÜĎ 1))

   Calling ‚ÄėM-x uniline-draw-plus‚Äô will result in this nice little
plus-shape:



      ‚ē≠‚ēģ
     ‚ē≠‚ēĮ‚ēį‚ēģ
     ‚ēį‚ēģ‚ē≠‚ēĮ
      ‚ēį‚ēĮ
     generated by
     M-x uniline-draw-plus

   We may modify the function to accept the size of the shape as a
parameter:

     (defun uniline-draw-plus (size)
       (interactive "Nsize? ")
       (uniline-write-ri‚Üí size)
       (uniline-write-dw‚Üď size)
       (uniline-write-ri‚Üí size)
       (uniline-write-dw‚Üď size)
       (uniline-write-lf‚Üź size)
       (uniline-write-dw‚Üď size)
       (uniline-write-lf‚Üź size)
       (uniline-write-up‚ÜĎ size)
       (uniline-write-lf‚Üź size)
       (uniline-write-up‚ÜĎ size)
       (uniline-write-ri‚Üí size)
       (uniline-write-up‚ÜĎ size))

   The ‚Äė(interactive "Nsize? ")‚Äô form prompts user for the size of the
shape if not given as a parameter.

   This API works in any mode, not only in ‚ÄėUniline‚Äô minor mode.  It
takes care of the infiniteness of the buffer in the right and down
directions.


